    • scott
      5.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      Impressive Speaker
      Reviewed in the United States on January 12, 2025
      Color: Black
      I work as a grill cook, which means Im in a very noisy environment. So I need a speaker that is very loud. And I can say this speaker gets very loud for its size, but is never harsh on the ears, like some other speakers which leave an almost ringing in your ears after a... See more
      I work as a grill cook, which means Im in a very noisy environment. So I need a speaker that is very loud. And I can say this speaker gets very loud for its size, but is never harsh on the ears, like some other speakers which leave an almost ringing in your ears after a high note. And it does not distort at max volume which is a plus for me.
      I used to have a 50w Rave Neo from soundcore, until recently when I sold it to a coworker who was in need of a good speaker. I had it for nearly 5 years. When I had it, I was constantly getting compliments on how impressive that speaker sounded. So I decided to buy another speaker from Anker since its quality I can trust.
      Comparing to the 50w Rave Neo, both with bass boost, and boom 2 out of box sound profile. The boom 2 gets louder than the rave Neo, however gets a little muddier at high volumes, while the rave Neo keeps a fuller sound. Probably due to the fact the boom 2 is missing a full range driver, and only has tweeters and a racetrack subwoofer. However does not matter in my use case. The battery life seems the same, after 3 hours of use at high volumes with bass on, I only used 40% of the battery on the boom 2, while I also used 40% of the rave Neo. Portability goes to the Boom 2. It is only the length of a ruler, height of 3/4 of a ruler, and is fairly slim. so it fits on any standard sized table easily, it also weighs less than half what the rave Neo weighs. The rave Neo felt like a workout carrying it work, while the boom 2 is easily carried by one finger. I also give appearances to the boom 2. The metal grill on the boom 2 feels very rugged and is much superior to the metal grill on the rave Neo. Both plastics feel the same as well, however it does seem the boom 2 is more vulnerable to scuffs and marks as I already have a scuff on the boom 2 with only 3 hours of use, while I have never gotten a scuff on the rave Neo. The LIGHTSHOW. The boom 2 is amazing to watch as it lights up and moves the radiators to the music. Very nice touch since I never really enjoyed the lights on the rave Neo. The rave Neo was also impressive, but the diffusion on the boom 2 looks very premium. Charging. Both charge with an input of usb type c. However, with the rave Neo, you had to use a usb type A charging block, which was super annoying because I have been trying to get away from usb type a, and micro usb. Type c charging blocks and cords are worlds superior. And the boom 2 can charge from any type c charging block.
      Sound. The boom 2 is loud. It is not audiophile quality. But if you plan on sticking it in the corner of the room or on the outside of a basketball court, you might not feel or hear every instrument or every vocal chord in a singers throat, but I guarantee you will be satisfied with the volume of music you are receiving from this speaker, which does sound very pleasant at least, which is what this speaker is meant to do. Get loud, so you can listen to music while you are doing other activities. I highly recommend higher end soundcore speakers, cant go wrong.

      As a long-time enthusiast of Soundcore products, I've consistently been impressed by their unbeatable combination of quality and value, and the Soundcore Boom2 Bluetooth speaker has only deepened my appreciation. Having owned multiple Soundcore speakers, I've come to expect a certain level of durability and sound excellence from this brand. The Boom2, a recent addition to my collection, lives up to these expectations and even surpasses them in many respects.

      The Soundcore Boom2 emerges as a formidable successor to the Motion+, which I've enjoyed for its compact size and reliable performance. However, I often found myself craving a bit more power, especially for outdoor uses like beach outings. The Boom2 has proven to be the perfect solution. It retains the portability I loved in the Motion+, but with an added punch that makes all the difference.

      The build quality of the Boom2 is robust, maintaining the solid feel that Soundcore is known for. It's sturdy enough to handle the occasional splash or drop, which is essential for any portable speaker I take to the beach. The design is both sleek and functional, making it a visually appealing addition to my gadget collection.

      Sound quality, which is a crucial factor for me, is where the Boom2 truly shines. Even against the backdrop of noisy beach waves, the clarity and depth of the sound are remarkable. The bass is rich and immersive, providing that full-bodied sound that music enthusiasts look for in a portable speaker. What's impressive is that this excellent audio performance comes at just 60% volume, indicating that the speaker can handle even larger gatherings without any compromise in sound fidelity.

      The Boom2's battery life is another highlight, lasting long enough to ensure continuous play for multiple 4-6 hour days without frequent recharges. This makes it not only great for a day at the beach but also for longer trips where charging options might be limited.

      The Soundcore Boom2 is a stellar portable Bluetooth speaker that offers great sound, durability, and value for money. It's an ideal choice for anyone looking to upgrade from the Motion+ or any other portable speaker. Whether it's for beach parties, casual gatherings, or just enjoying music at home, the Boom2 is more than adequate to meet all your audio needs. I highly recommend this speaker to anyone in search of quality sound on the go.

    • Einstein1
      4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
      The Best Bluetooth speakr I've owned. Not perfect but still really good for the money.
      Reviewed in the United States on December 16, 2024
      Color: Black
      Just to preface, this is primarily a sound quality review. Out of the box, before break-in and adjustment, this unit has a somewhat recessed midrange and a very metallic sound to the upper midrange/treble. The bass is plentiful, clean, deep, and tight thanks in part to... See more
      Just to preface, this is primarily a sound quality review.
      Out of the box, before break-in and adjustment, this unit has a somewhat recessed midrange and a very metallic sound to the upper midrange/treble. The bass is plentiful, clean, deep, and tight thanks in part to decent amplification as well as the proper coupling of the twin passive bass radiators with the racetrack-style bass driver. The bass radiators also show the different "light show" modes on either side of the speaker. I found the flame mode produces a nice almost lowkey fireplace like ambiance. However, all is not lost about the mids and highs. If you are a more sophisticated or discriminating music listener ,who also understands what real instruments and voices are supposed to sound like and you can exercise a small amount of patience it takes to use the equalizer in the included application you can overcome the somewhat cold-sounding midrange and highs.
      I am a concert sound engineer and as such I know what music is supposed to sound like, I like hearing every instrument, voice, and the nuances thereof such as the contact of a bow across strings, the contact of a drumstick against a drum head, and the breath of a jazz singer, so I chose to utilize the included multiband equalizer to correct the speaker's response I was able to achieve a much smoother and more detailed response. Rather than being shouty or cold sounding the speaker was now much smoother, more dynamic, and a lot more listenable.
      Overall, the Soundcore Boom 2 is enjoyable to listen to upon proper calibration. The BassUp 2.0 is also very nice, it seems to help the overall sound rather than hinder it, so many bass boost functions are a hindrance to the overall sonic signature of otherwise decent-sounding speakers. This is clearly a speaker designed for those who want a very loud, clear compact/lightweight, and portable speaker. While not necessarily an audiophile product, it can be an inexpensive opinion for the music lover who knows what music is supposed to sound like and will spend a little time to properly calibrate it to their liking. The "Soundcore Signature" preset will provide you with reasonably good fidelity You will also be able to further adjust things to your liking by choosing the multiband EQ or presets.
      Bluetooth pairing with my Samsung Galaxy S24+ was easy and uneventful, the unit also prompted me to download the Soundcore app upon connecting to it. Overall operation whether with the hardware buttons on the unit or through the app is simple. I have not done an ultimate volume test due to not being appropriate for my environment at the time, however, the Boom2 does give the impression that it possesses more than enough power and efficiency to produce high volumes when asked to do so without strain at least within the 1st 50% of it's volume.

      Finally the quality of sound on a phone call was clean, albeit a little nasal blame the persons voice more than the speaker though., as a matter of fact, this was my first time usage of this unit. Also, the unit also feels sturdy, but not overly heavy.it is light enough to be carried around all day to all of your events. If you are seeking an excellent value in a Bluetooth speaker THIS IS IT, GO BUY ONE!
